# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana-ketchup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana-ketchup/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:banana-ketchup/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:banana-ketchup/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:banana-ketchup/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The names mean 'garlic and oil' in Catalan and Provençal.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] It is found in the cuisines of southeastern France (Provence, Languedoc, Roussillon) and eastern Spain (traditionally Catalonia and to a lesser extent the Valencian Community, the Balearic Islands, Murcia, and eastern Andalusia).
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Some versions of the sauce are closer to a garlic mayonnaise, incorporating egg yolks and lemon juice, while other versions omit egg yolk and contain more garlic.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The garlic gives the sauce a pastier texture, making it more laborious to produce as the emulsion is harder to stabilise.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] There are many variations, such as adding lemon juice or other seasonings.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] In Malta, arjoli or ajjoli is quite different; it is made with galletti (a type of cracker), tomato, onion, garlic, and herbs.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Like mayonnaise, aioli is an emulsion or suspension of small globules of oil and oil-soluble compounds in water and water-soluble compounds.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Many older recipes do not include egg, but nowadays, egg or egg yolk is the usual emulsifier.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Since about 1990, it has become common in the United States to call all flavored mayonnaises *aioli*.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Purists insist that true aioli must contain garlic and no other seasoning (except salt).
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] In the form *aioli*, the word is a compound of Provençal *ai* 'garlic' and *oli* 'oil'.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The English spelling comes from the French *aïoli*, which is an adaptation of an Occitan term.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The spelling in Occitan may be *alhòli*, following the classical norm, or *aiòli*, following the Mistralian norm.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] In Catalan it is spelled *allioli* (pronounced [ˌaʎiˈɔli]).
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The most common term in Spanish is *alioli*, an adaptation from Catalan, although there are alternative Spanish terms such as *ajoaceite*, *ajiaceite*, *ajolio* or *ajaceite*.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] It is also spelled *alioli* in Galician.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Garlic is crushed in a mortar and pestle and emulsified with salt and olive oil.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Today, aioli is often made in a food processor or blender, but some traditionalists object that this does not give the same result.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] In Occitan cuisine, *aioli* is typically served with seafood, fish soup, and croutons.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] An example is a dish called *merluça amb alhòli*.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] In the Occitan Alps it is served with potatoes boiled with salt and bay laurel.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] This dish is often served during the festivities on the feast days of the patron saint of Provençal villages and towns.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] It is traditional to serve it with snails for Christmas Eve and with cod on Ash Wednesday.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Aïoli is so strongly associated with Provence that when the poet Frédéric Mistral started a regionalist Provençal-language newspaper in 1891, he called it *L'Aiòli*.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] The Provençal cuisine fish soup bourride is generally served with *aioli*.
[src:banana-ketchup/aioli] Other commonly used vegetables are beets, fennel, celery, zucchini, cauliflower, chickpeas, and raw tomatoes.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] The dish is also prepared in Sakarya, Turkey among the Abaza people and is patented by the Turkish Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] In 2018, ajika was included on the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Georgia list.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] The word *ajika* comes from the Abkhaz language and means 'salt'.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] However, in the Mingrelian language, a sharp linguistic distinction is maintained: the native word for salt is **jim** (ჯიმჷ), while *ajika* (აჯიკა) refers exclusively to the spicy condiment.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] While the name is a Northwest Caucasian loanword, the dish is a defining staple of Mingrelian cuisine.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] In the Abkhaz language, the condiment is formally known as **apyrpyl-jika** (pepper-salt), whereas the standalone term *ajika* became the standardized name for the specific Mingrelian preparation.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajika] This distinction confirms that in the Mingrelian tradition, Ajika is not a synonym for salt, but a unique, processed condiment.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Homemade ajvar is made of roasted peppers.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Depending on the capsaicin content in bell peppers and the amount of added chili peppers, it can be sweet (traditional), piquant (the most common), or very hot.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Ajvar can be consumed as a bread spread or as a side dish.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] One variation contains tomato and eggplant, and another green bell peppers and oregano.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] "Homemade Leskovac Ajvar" and "Macedonian Ajvar" are registered with the World Intellectual Property Organization in order to protect their brand names.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] The name *ajvar* comes from the Turkish word *havyar*, which means "salted roe, caviar" and shares an etymology with "caviar", coming from the Persian word *xaviyar*.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Before the 20th century, significant local production of caviar occurred on the Danube, with sturgeon swimming from the Black Sea up to Belgrade.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Domestic *ajvar*, meaning "caviar", used to be a very popular dish in Belgrade homes and restaurants, but the domestic production of caviar became unsteady in the 1890s because of labor disputes.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Eventually a special pepper salad was offered as a substitute in Belgrade restaurants under the name "red ajvar" (*crveni ajvar*) or "Serbian ajvar" (*srpski ajvar*).
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Homemade ajvar is made of peppers that are roasted, minced, and then cooked, but some industrial producers use fresh minced peppers, which are only cooked with sunflower oil afterwards, which leads to lower quality.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Ajvar preparation is somewhat difficult, because it requires considerable manual labour, particularly for peeling the roasted peppers.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] It is traditionally prepared in mid-autumn, when peppers are most abundant, and preserved in glass jars for consumption throughout the year.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Anecdotally, most households' stocks do not last until the spring, when fresh vegetables become available, so it is usually eaten as a winter food.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Entire families or neighbours often gather to prepare the peppers together.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] The traditional cultivar of pepper used is called *roga* (approx.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] *Roga* is large, red, horn-shaped and relatively easy to peel, with thick flesh.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] To produce ajvar, fresh peppers are roasted whole on a plate above an open fire, a plate of wood in a stove, or in an oven.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] The baked peppers must briefly cool to allow the flesh to separate from the skin.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Next, the skin is carefully peeled off and the seeds are removed.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] The peppers are then ground in a mill or chopped into tiny pieces (this variant is often referred to as pindjur).
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Finally, the resulting mash is stewed for several hours in large pots.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Sunflower oil is added at this stage to condense and reduce the water, and to enhance later preservation.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Salt is added at the end (sometimes alongside vinegar), and the hot mush is poured directly into sterilized glass jars, which are sealed immediately.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Ajvar is produced in most Balkan countries, including Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, North Macedonia and Serbia.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] It is also produced in Slovenia where it became widely known during the Yugoslav period.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Serbia's reported annual production is 640 tons.
[src:banana-ketchup/ajvar] Ajvar is often included as part of *zimnica* (winter foods), which include pickled chili peppers, pickled tomatoes, and anything else that can be preserved in a jar just before winter.
[src:banana-ketchup/banana-ketchup] In Filipino households, this condiment is used on many dishes: Filipino spaghetti, omelettes (*torta*), hot dogs, hamburgers, french fries, fish, charcoal-grilled pork barbecue, Filipino barbecue, fried chicken, and other meats.
[src:banana-ketchup/banana-ketchup] Orosa (1892–1945) is credited with inventing the product.
[src:banana-ketchup/banana-ketchup] In 1942, banana ketchup was first mass-produced commercially by Magdalo V.
[src:banana-ketchup/banana-ketchup] Francisco Sr. who founded the brand name Mafran (a portmanteau of his given name and surname).
[src:banana-ketchup/banana-ketchup] Reyes to expand his business and therefore the Universal Food Corporation (UFC, now a brand under NutriAsia) was formed in 1969.
